To determine its structure, compound 2 was purified from AabrSPS - transformed yeast cultures by column chromatography and analyzed by NMR spectroscopy. As shown in Figs. S17–S27 and Supplementary Table S4, correlations observed in COSY and HMBC NMR spectra revealed the structure of this compound to be silphiperfol-5-ene. Correlations between H-1, H-14, and H- 15 in the NOESY spectrum of 2 determined the relative configurations at C-1, C-14, and C-15 to be S* , R* , and R* , respectively. Likewise, correlations between H-11a, H-11b, and H-12 revealed the relative configurations at C-4 and C-8 to be S* and R* , respectively. This interpretation matches those of previously reported NMR spectroscopic data of 7- epi -silphiperfol-5-ene (
;
;
). Thus, compound 2 was identified as 7- epi -silphiperfol-5-ene ( Fig. 4C ), indicating that AabrSPS is a 7- epi -silphiperfol-5-ene synthase.

Triquinane-type sesquiterpenes have attracted a great deal of attention due to their unique tricyclopentane ring structure featuring several stereogenic centers. So far, MrTPS2 from chamomile is the only reported plant sesquiterpene synthase that catalyzes the cyclization of FPP into triquinane-type α- isocomene (

) via 1,11- and 2,10-ring closures that generate the caryophyllenyl cation, followed by a multi-step carbocationic cyclization/rearrangement (
Fig. 5
