In vivo
functional analysis confirmed our speculation based on phylogenetic analysis that the enzymatic function of AabrSPS differs from those of AabrBOS1–4. AabrSPS is also more closely related to AaQHS1, MrTPS2, and AaECS1 than AabrBOS1–4 (
Fig. 3
), suggesting conserved amino acid residues among AabrSPS, AaQHS1, MrTPS2, and AaECS1, but different from AabrBOS1–4, may possess key functions important for 1) controlling the initial cyclization of FPP to be 1,11- cyclization as does AaQHS1 and 2) catalyzing the multi-step carbocationic cyclization/rearrangements as do MrTPS2 and AaECS1. In addition to the conserved motifs initiating FPP ionization, several attempts have been made to identify the catalytic residues of sesquiterpene synthase. As a result, those involved in the initialization of 1,6- and 1,10-cyclizations and directing the catalytic cascades have been reported (

; 

; 

; 

). However, following amino acid sequence alignment, most of the residues of AabrSPS corresponding to the catalytic sites of the reported enzymes are identical, particularly among enzymes isolated from 

A
. 
abrotanum

(asterisks and black, green, and blue triangles in 
Figs. 2 and S2
). This suggests that the catalytic sites of AabrSPS and AabrBOS1–4 may be located elsewhere or that the catalytic residues of sesquiterpene synthase are not yet fully understood. In a similar manner to previous reports of pentalenene, aristolochene, and trichodiene synthases, X-ray crystallography of all sesquiterpene synthases identified in this study may be required for the identification of key catalytic residues important for the conformation of the active site cavity (

; 

; 

; 

). Molecular docking in combination with quantum chemical calculation is also a useful technique to predict FPP and the following carbocation intermediate orientations in the substrate binding site and can provide a clearer picture of sesquiterpene synthases' catalytic mechanism towards FPP (

; 

; 

; 

, 

; 

). Reciprocal site-directed mutagenesis between AabrBOS1–4 and AabrSPS/MrTPS2 at certain conserved residues among AabrBOS1–4 (highlighted in pink in 
Fig. 2
) differing in AabrSPS and MrTPS2 (only residues conserved in AabrSPS and MrTPS2 are highlighted in yellow in 
Fig. 2
) is also of interest.

